As already mentioned in section (5.1); this is special case of dipole-dipole interaction.", "fibs": ["interaction"]}
{"text": "We have already learnt about this in Unit 4.", "fibs": ["learnt"]}
{"text": "Although hydrogen bonding is regarded as being limited to N, O and F; but species such as  may also participate in hydrogen bonding.", "fibs": ["hydrogen"]}
{"text": "Energy of hydrogen bond varies between 10 to 100 kJ mol–1.", "fibs": ["hydrogen"]}
{"text": "This is quite a significant amount of energy; therefore, hydrogen bonds are powerful force in determining the structure and properties of many compounds, for example proteins and nucleic acids.", "fibs": ["amount"]}
{"text": "Strength of the hydrogen bond is determined by the coulombic interaction between the lone-pair electrons of the electronegative atom of one molecule and the hydrogen atom of other molecule.", "fibs": ["Strength"]}
{"text": "Following diagram shows the formation of hydrogen bond.", "fibs": ["diagram"]}
{"text": "When two molecules are brought into close contact with each other, the repulsion between the electron clouds and that between the nuclei of two molecules comes into play.", "fibs": ["contact"]}
{"text": "Magnitude of the repulsion rises very rapidly as the distance separating the molecules decreases.", "fibs": ["Magnitude"]}
{"text": "This is the reason that liquids and solids are hard to compress.", "fibs": ["reason"]}
{"text": "In these states molecules are already in close contact; therefore they resist further compression; as that would result in the increase of repulsive interactions.", "fibs": ["contact"]}
{"text": "5.2  Thermal Energy
Thermal energy is the energy of a body arising from motion of its atoms or molecules.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "It is directly proportional to the temperature of the substance.", "fibs": ["temperature"]}
{"text": "It is the measure of averagekinetic energy of the particles of the matter and is thus responsible for movement of particles.", "fibs": ["measure"]}
{"text": "This movement of particles is called thermal motion.", "fibs": ["movement"]}
{"text": "5.3	Intermolecular Forces vs Thermal Interactions
We have already learnt that intermolecular forces tend to keep the molecules together but thermal energy of the molecules tends to keep them apart.", "fibs": ["learnt"]}
{"text": "Three states of matter are the result of balance between intermolecular forces and the thermal energy of the molecules.", "fibs": ["matter"]}
{"text": "When molecular interactions are very weak, molecules do not cling together to make liquid or solid unless thermal energy is reduced by lowering the temperature.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "Gases do not liquify on compression only, although molecules come very close to each other and intermolecular forces operate to the maximum.", "fibs": ["compression"]}
{"text": "However, when thermal energy of molecules is reduced by lowering the temperature; the gases can be very easily liquified.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "Predominance of thermal energy and the molecular interaction energy of a substance in three states is depicted as follows :





We have already learnt the cause for the existence of the three states of matter.", "fibs": ["Predominance"]}
{"text": "Now we will learn more about gaseous and liquid states and the laws which govern the behaviour of matter in these states.", "fibs": ["behaviour"]}
{"text": "We shall deal with the solid state in class XII.", "fibs": ["deal"]}
{"text": "5.4 The Gaseous State
This is the simplest state of matter.", "fibs": ["state"]}
{"text": "Throughout our life we remain immersed in the ocean of air which is a mixture of gases.", "fibs": ["life"]}
{"text": "We spend our life in the lowermost layer of the atmosphere  called troposphere, which is held to the surface of the earth by gravitational force.", "fibs": ["life"]}
{"text": "The thin layer of atmosphere is vital to our life.", "fibs": ["layer"]}
{"text": "It shields us from harmful radiations and contains substances like dioxygen, dinitrogen, carbon dioxide, water vapour, etc.", "fibs": ["dioxygen"]}
{"text": "Let us now focus our attention on the behaviour of substances which exist in the gaseous state under normal conditions of temperature and pressure.", "fibs": ["focus"]}
{"text": "A look at the periodic table shows that only eleven elements exist as gases under normal conditions (Fig 5.4).", "fibs": ["table"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "5.4 Eleven elements that exist as gases


The gaseous state is characterized by the following physical properties.", "fibs": ["state"]}
{"text": "• Gases are highly compressible.", "fibs": ["•"]}
{"text": "•	Gases exert pressure equally in all directions.", "fibs": ["•"]}
{"text": "•	Gases have much lower density than the solids and liquids.", "fibs": ["•"]}
{"text": "•	The volume and the shape of  gases are not fixed.", "fibs": ["•"]}
{"text": "These assume volume and shape of the container.", "fibs": ["volume"]}
{"text": "•	Gases mix evenly and completely in all proportions without any mechanical aid.", "fibs": ["•"]}
{"text": "Simplicity of gases is due to the fact that the forces of interaction between their molecules  are negligible.", "fibs": ["Simplicity"]}
{"text": "Their behaviour is governed by same general laws, which were discovered as a result of their experimental studies.", "fibs": ["behaviour"]}
{"text": "Some of  these properties like pressure, volume, temperature and mass are very important because relationships between these variables describe state of the gas.", "fibs": ["pressure"]}
{"text": "Interdependence of these variables leads to the formulation of gas laws.", "fibs": ["Interdependence"]}
{"text": "In the next section we will learn about gas laws.", "fibs": ["section"]}
{"text": "5.5  The Gas Laws
The gas laws which we will study now are the result of research carried on for several centuries on the physical properties of gases.", "fibs": ["gas"]}
{"text": "The first reliable measurement on properties of gases was made by Anglo-Irish scientist Robert Boyle in 1662.", "fibs": ["measurement"]}
{"text": "The law which he formulated is known as Boyle’s Law.", "fibs": ["law"]}
{"text": "Later on attempts to fly in air with the help of hot air balloons motivated Jaccques Charles and Joseph Lewis Gay Lussac to discover additional gas laws.", "fibs": ["air"]}
{"text": "Contribution from Avogadro and others provided lot of information about gaseous state.", "fibs": ["lot"]}
