5.5.2	Charles’ Law (Temperature - Volume Relationship)
Charles and Gay Lussac performed several experiments on gases independently to improve upon hot air balloon technology.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "Their investigations showed that for a fixed mass of a gas at constant pressure, volume of a gas increases on increasing temperature and decreases on cooling.", "fibs": ["mass"]}
{"text": "They found that for each degree rise in temperature, volume of a gas increases by  of the original volume of the gas at 0 °C.", "fibs": ["degree"]}
{"text": "Thus if volumes of the gas at 0 °C and at t °C are V0 and Vt respectively, then


At this stage, we define a new scale of temperature such that t °C on new scale is given by T = 273.15 + t and 0 °C will be given byT0 = 273.15.", "fibs": ["gas"]}
{"text": "This new temperature scale is called the Kelvin temperature scale or Absolute temperature scale.", "fibs": ["temperature"]}
{"text": "Thus 0°C on the celsius scale is equal to 273.15 K at the absolute scale.", "fibs": ["scale"]}
{"text": "Note that degree sign is not used while writing the temperature in absolute temperature scale, i.e., Kelvin scale.", "fibs": ["degree"]}
{"text": "Kelvin scale of temperature is also called Thermodynamic scale of temperature and is used in all scientific works.", "fibs": ["scale"]}
{"text": "Thus we add 273 (more precisely 273.15) to the celsius temperature to obtain temperature at Kelvin scale.", "fibs": ["temperature"]}
