5.8	Kinetic Molecular Theory of Gases
So far we have learnt the laws (e.g., Boyle’s law, Charles’ law etc.)", "fibs": ["speed"]}
{"text": "which are concise statements of experimental facts observed in the laboratory by the scientists.", "fibs": ["laboratory"]}
{"text": "Conducting careful experiments is an important aspect of scientific method and it tells us how the particular system is behaving under different conditions.", "fibs": ["aspect"]}
{"text": "However, once the experimental facts are established, a scientist is curious to know why the system is behaving in that way.", "fibs": ["scientist"]}
{"text": "For example, gas laws help us to predict that pressure increases when we compress gases but we would like to know what happens at molecular level when a gas is compressed ?", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "A theory is constructed to answer such questions.", "fibs": ["theory"]}
{"text": "A theory is a model (i.e., a mental picture) that enables us to better understand our observations.", "fibs": ["theory"]}
{"text": "The theory that attempts to elucidate the behaviour of gases is known as kinetic molecular theory.", "fibs": ["theory"]}
{"text": "Assumptions or postulates of the kinetic-molecular theory of gases are given below.", "fibs": ["theory"]}
{"text": "These postulates are related to atoms and molecules which cannot be seen, hence it is said to provide a microscopic model of gases.", "fibs": ["model"]}
{"text": "•	Gases consist of large number of identical particles (atoms or molecules) that are so small and so far apart on the average that the actual volume of the molecules is negligible in comparison to the empty space between them.", "fibs": ["•"]}
{"text": "They are considered as point masses.", "fibs": ["point"]}
{"text": "This assumption explains the great compressibility of gases.", "fibs": ["assumption"]}
{"text": "•	There is no force of attraction between the particles of a gas at ordinary temperature and pressure.", "fibs": ["•"]}
{"text": "The support for this assumption comes from the fact that gases expand and occupy all the space available to them.", "fibs": ["support"]}
{"text": "•	Particles of a gas are always in constant and random motion.", "fibs": ["•"]}
{"text": "If the particles were at rest and occupied fixed positions, then a gas would have had a fixed shape which is not observed.", "fibs": ["rest"]}
{"text": "•	Particles of a gas move in all possible directions in straight lines.", "fibs": ["•"]}
{"text": "During their random motion, they collide with each other and with the walls of the container.", "fibs": ["motion"]}
{"text": "Pressure is exerted by the gas as a result of collision of the particles with the walls of the container.", "fibs": ["Pressure"]}
{"text": "•	Collisions of gas molecules are perfectly elastic.", "fibs": ["•"]}
{"text": "This means that total energy of molecules before and after the collision remains same.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "There may be exchange of energy between colliding molecules, their individual energies may change, but the sum of their energies remains constant.", "fibs": ["exchange"]}
{"text": "If there were loss of kinetic energy, the motion of molecules will stop and gases will settle down.", "fibs": ["loss"]}
{"text": "•	At any particular time, different particles in the gas have different speeds and hence different kinetic energies.", "fibs": ["•"]}
{"text": "This assumption is reasonable because as the particles collide, we expect their speed to change.", "fibs": ["assumption"]}
{"text": "Even if initial speed of all the particles was same, the molecular collisions will disrupt this uniformity.", "fibs": ["speed"]}
{"text": "It is possible to show that though the individual speeds are changing, the distribution of speeds remains constant at a particular temperature.", "fibs": ["show"]}
{"text": "•	If a molecule has variable speed, then it must have a variable kinetic energy.", "fibs": ["•"]}
{"text": "Under these circumstances, we can talk only about average kinetic energy.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "In kinetic theory, it is assumed that average kinetic energy of the gas molecules is directly proportional to the absolute temperature.", "fibs": ["theory"]}
{"text": "It is seen that on heating a gas at constant volume, the pressure increases.", "fibs": ["heating"]}
{"text": "On heating the gas, kinetic energy of the particles increases and these strike the walls of the container more frequently, thus, exerting more pressure.", "fibs": ["heating"]}
{"text": "Kinetic theory of gases allows us to derive theoretically, all the gas laws studied in the previous sections.", "fibs": ["theory"]}
{"text": "Calculations and predictions based on kinetic theory of gases agree very well with the experimental observations and thus establish the correctness of this model.", "fibs": ["theory"]}
{"text": "5.9	Behaviour of real gases: Deviation from ideal gas behaviour
Our theoritical model of gases corresponds very well with the experimental observations.", "fibs": ["Behaviour"]}
{"text": "Difficulty arises when we try to test how far the relation pV = nRT reproduce actual pressure-volume-temperature relationshipof gases.", "fibs": ["Difficulty"]}
{"text": "To test this point we plot pV vs p plot of  gases because at constant temperature, pV will be constant (Boyle’s law) and pV vs p graph at all pressures will be a straight line parallel to x-axis.", "fibs": ["test"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "5.10 shows such a plot constructed from actual data for several gases at 273 K.
It can be seen easily that at constant temperature pV vs p plot for real gases is not a straight line.", "fibs": ["plot"]}
{"text": "There is a significant deviation from ideal behaviour.", "fibs": ["deviation"]}
{"text": "In the curves for dihydrogen and helium, as the pressure increases the value of pV also increases.", "fibs": ["dihydrogen"]}
{"text": "The second type of plot is seen in the case of other gases like carbon monoxide and methane.", "fibs": ["type"]}
{"text": "In these plots first there is a negative deviation from ideal behaviour, the pV value decreases with increase in pressure and reaches to a minimum value characteristic of a gas.", "fibs": ["deviation"]}
{"text": "After that pV value starts increasing.", "fibs": ["pV"]}
{"text": "The curve then crosses the line for ideal gas and after that shows positive deviation continuously.", "fibs": ["curve"]}
{"text": "It is thus, found that real gases do not follow ideal gas equation perfectly under all conditions.", "fibs": ["gas"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "5.10 Plot of  pV vs p for real gas and ideal gas



Deviation from ideal behaviour also becomes apparent when pressure vs volume plot is drawn.", "fibs": ["Plot"]}
{"text": "The pressure vs volume plot of experimental data (real gas) and that theoretically calculated from Boyle’s law (ideal gas) should coincide.", "fibs": ["pressure"]}
{"text": "Fig 5.11 shows these plots.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "It is apparent that at very high pressure the measured volume is more than the calculated volume.", "fibs": ["pressure"]}
{"text": "At low pressures, measured and calculated volumes approach each other.", "fibs": ["approach"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "5.11 Plot of pressure vs volume for real gas           	  and ideal gas



It is found that real gases do not follow, Boyle’s law, Charles law and Avogadro law perfectly under all conditions.", "fibs": ["Plot"]}
{"text": "(i) Why do gases deviate from the ideal behaviour?", "fibs": ["behaviour"]}
{"text": "(ii) What are the conditions under which gases deviate from ideality?", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "We get the answer of the first question if we look into postulates of kinetic theory once again.", "fibs": ["answer"]}
{"text": "We find that two assumptions of the kinetic theory do not hold good.", "fibs": ["theory"]}
{"text": "These are

(a) There is no force of attraction between the molecules of a gas.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "(b)	Volume of the molecules of a gas is negligibly small in comparison to the space occupied by the gas.", "fibs": ["b"]}
{"text": "If assumption (a) is correct, the gas will never liquify.", "fibs": ["assumption"]}
{"text": "This means that forces of repulsion are powerful enough and prevent squashing of molecules in tiny volume.", "fibs": ["repulsion"]}
{"text": "If assumption (b) is correct, the pressure vs volume graph of experimental data (real gas) and that theoritically calculated from Boyles law (ideal gas) should coincide.", "fibs": ["assumption"]}
{"text": "Real gases show deviations from ideal gas law because molecules interact with each other.", "fibs": ["show"]}
{"text": "At high pressure, molecules do not strike the walls of the container with full impact because these are dragged back by other molecules due to molecular attractive forces.", "fibs": ["pressure"]}
{"text": "This affects the pressure exerted by the molecules on the walls of the container.", "fibs": ["pressure"]}
{"text": "Thus, the pressure exerted by the gas is lower than the pressure exerted by the ideal gas.", "fibs": ["pressure"]}
{"text": "Repulsive interactions are short-range interactions and are significant when molecules are almost in contact.", "fibs": ["contact"]}
{"text": "This is the situation at high pressure.", "fibs": ["situation"]}
{"text": "The repulsive forces cause the molecules to behave as small but impenetrable spheres.", "fibs": ["cause"]}
{"text": "The volume occupied by the molecules also becomes significant because instead of moving in volume V, these are now restricted to volume (V–nb) where nb is approximately the total volume occupied by the molecules themselves.", "fibs": ["volume"]}
{"text": "Here, b is a constant.", "fibs": ["b"]}
{"text": "Having taken into account the corrections for pressure and volume, we can rewrite equation (5.17) as




Equation (5.31) is known as van der Waals equation.", "fibs": ["account"]}
{"text": "In this equation n is number of moles of the gas.", "fibs": ["equation"]}
{"text": "Constants a and b are called van der Waals constants and their value depends on the characteristic of a gas.", "fibs": ["b"]}
{"text": "Value of ‘a’ is measure of magnitude of intermolecular attractive forces within the gas and is independent of temperature and pressure.", "fibs": ["‘"]}
{"text": "Also, at very low temperature, intermolecular forces become significant.", "fibs": ["temperature"]}
{"text": "As the molecules travel with low average speed, these can be captured by one another due to attractive forces.", "fibs": ["travel"]}
{"text": "Real gases show ideal behaviour when conditions of temperature and pressure are such that the intermolecular forces are practically negligible.", "fibs": ["show"]}
{"text": "The real gases show ideal behaviour when pressure approaches zero.", "fibs": ["show"]}
{"text": "The deviation from ideal behaviour can be measured in terms of compressibility factor Z, which is the ratio of product pV and nRT.", "fibs": ["deviation"]}
{"text": "Mathematically 
                                     (5.32)
For ideal gas Z = 1 at all temperatures and pressures because pV = n RT.", "fibs": ["gas"]}
{"text": "The graph of Z vs p will be a straight line parallel to pressure axis (Fig.", "fibs": ["graph"]}
{"text": "5.12, page 152).", "fibs": ["page"]}
{"text": "For gases which deviate from ideality, value of Z  deviates from unity.", "fibs": ["ideality"]}
{"text": "At very low pressures all gases shown have Z ≈1  and behave as ideal gas.", "fibs": ["≈1"]}
{"text": "At high pressure all the gases have Z > 1.", "fibs": ["pressure"]}
{"text": "Thus gases show ideal behaviour when the volume occupied is large so that the volume of the molecules can be neglected in comparison to it.", "fibs": ["show"]}
{"text": "In other words, the behaviour of the gas becomes more ideal when pressure is very low.", "fibs": ["behaviour"]}
{"text": "Upto what pressure a gas will follow the ideal gas law, depends upon nature of the gas and its temperature.", "fibs": ["pressure"]}
{"text": "The temperature at which a real gas obeys ideal gas law over an appreciable range of pressure is called Boyle temperature or Boyle point.", "fibs": ["temperature"]}
{"text": "Boyle point of a gas depends upon its nature.", "fibs": ["point"]}
{"text": "Above their Boyle point, real gases show positive deviations from ideality and Z values are greater than one.", "fibs": ["point"]}
{"text": "The forces of attraction between the molecules are very feeble.", "fibs": ["attraction"]}
{"text": "Below Boyle temperature real gases first show decrease in Z  value with increasing pressure, which reaches a minimum value.", "fibs": ["temperature"]}
{"text": "On further increase in pressure, the value of Z  increases continuously.", "fibs": ["increase"]}
{"text": "Above explanation shows that at low pressure and high temperature gases show ideal behaviour.", "fibs": ["explanation"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
