{"text": "5.11.2 Surface Tension 
It is well known fact that liquids assume the shape of the container.", "fibs": ["Surface"]}
{"text": "Why is it then small drops of mercury form spherical bead instead of spreading on the surface.", "fibs": ["mercury"]}
{"text": "Why do particles of soil at the bottom of river remain separated but they stick together when taken out ?", "fibs": ["soil"]}
{"text": "Why does a liquid rise (or fall) in a thin capillary as soon as the capillary touches the surface of the liquid ?", "fibs": ["rise"]}
{"text": "All these phenomena are caused due to the characteristic property of liquids, called surface tension.", "fibs": ["property"]}
{"text": "A molecule in the bulk of liquid experiences equal intermolecular forces from all sides.", "fibs": ["molecule"]}
{"text": "The molecule, therefore does not experience any net force.", "fibs": ["molecule"]}
{"text": "But for the molecule on the surface of liquid, net attractive force is towards the interior of the liquid (Fig.", "fibs": ["molecule"]}
{"text": "Liquids tend to minimize their surface area.", "fibs": ["surface"]}
{"text": "The molecules on the surface experience a net downward force and have more energy than the molecules in the bulk, which do not experience any net force.", "fibs": ["surface"]}
{"text": "Therefore, liquids tend to have minimum number of molecules at their surface.", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "If surface of the liquid is increased by pulling a molecule from the bulk, attractive forces will have to be overcome.", "fibs": ["surface"]}
{"text": "This will require expenditure of energy.", "fibs": ["expenditure"]}
{"text": "The energy required to increase the surface area of the liquid by one unit is defined as surface energy.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "Its dimensions are J m–2.", "fibs": ["m–2"]}
{"text": "Surface tension is  defined as the force acting per unit length perpendicular to the line drawn on the surface of liquid.", "fibs": ["Surface"]}
{"text": "It is denoted by Greek letter γ (Gamma).", "fibs": ["letter"]}
{"text": "It has dimensions of kg s–2 and in SI unit it is expressed as N m–1.", "fibs": ["kg"]}
{"text": "The lowest energy state of the liquid will be when surface area is minimum.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "Spherical shape satisfies this condition, that is why mercury drops are spherical in shape.", "fibs": ["shape"]}
{"text": "This is the reason that sharp glass edges are heated for making them smooth.", "fibs": ["reason"]}
{"text": "On heating, the glass melts and the surface of the liquid tends to take the rounded shape at the edges, which makes the edges smooth.", "fibs": ["heating"]}
{"text": "This is called fire polishing of glass.", "fibs": ["fire"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "5.15 Forces acting on a molecule on liquid surface and on a molecule inside the liquid


Liquid tends to rise (or fall) in the capillary because of surface tension.", "fibs": ["molecule"]}
{"text": "Liquids wet the things because they spread across their surfaces as thin film.", "fibs": ["spread"]}
{"text": "Moist soil grains are pulled together because surface area of thin film of water is reduced.", "fibs": ["soil"]}
{"text": "It is surface tension which gives stretching property to the surface of a liquid.", "fibs": ["surface"]}
{"text": "On flat surface, droplets are slightly flattened by the effect of gravity; but in the gravity free environments drops are perfectly spherical.", "fibs": ["surface"]}
{"text": "The magnitude of surface tension of a liquid depends on the attractive forces between the molecules.", "fibs": ["magnitude"]}
{"text": "When the attractive forces are large, the surface tension is large.", "fibs": ["surface"]}
{"text": "Increase in temperature increases the kinetic energy of the molecules and effectiveness of intermolecular attraction decreases, so surface tension decreases as the temperature is raised.", "fibs": ["temperature"]}
{"text": "Viscosity is a measure of resistance to flow which arises due to the internal friction between layers of fluid as they slip past one another while liquid flows.", "fibs": ["Viscosity"]}
{"text": "Strong intermolecular forces between molecules hold them together and resist movement of layers past one another.", "fibs": ["movement"]}
{"text": "When a liquid flows over a fixed surface, the layer of molecules in the immediate contact of surface is stationary.", "fibs": ["surface"]}
{"text": "The velocity of upper layers increases as the distance of layers from the fixed layer increases.", "fibs": ["velocity"]}
{"text": "This type of flow in which there is a regular gradation of velocity in passing from one layer to the next is called laminar flow.", "fibs": ["type"]}
{"text": "If we choose any layer in the flowing liquid (Fig.5.16), the layer above it accelerates its flow and the layer below this retards its flow.", "fibs": ["layer"]}
{"text": "If the velocity of the layer at a distance dz is changed by a value du then velocity gradient is given by the amount .", "fibs": ["velocity"]}
{"text": "A force is required to maintain the flow of layers.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "This force is proportional to the area of contact of layers and velocity gradient i.e.", "fibs": ["force"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "5.16 Gradation of velocity in the laminar flow


’ is proportionality constant and is called coefficient of viscosity.", "fibs": ["velocity"]}
{"text": "Viscosity coefficient is the force when velocity gradient is unity and the area of contact is unit area.", "fibs": ["Viscosity"]}
{"text": "Thus ‘’ is measure of viscosity.", "fibs": ["‘"]}
{"text": "SI unit of viscosity coefficient is 1 newton second per square metre (N s m–2) = pascal second (Pa s = 1kg m–1s–1).", "fibs": ["SI"]}
{"text": "In cgs system the unit of coefficient of viscosity is poise (named after great scientist Jean Louise Poiseuille).", "fibs": ["system"]}
{"text": "1 poise = 1 g cm–1s–1 = 10–1kg m–1s–1
Greater the viscosity, the more slowly the liquid flows.", "fibs": ["poise"]}
{"text": "Hydrogen bonding and van der Waals forces are strong enough to cause high viscosity.", "fibs": ["Hydrogen"]}
{"text": "Viscosity of liquids decreases as the temperature rises because at high temperature molecules have high kinetic energy and can overcome the intermolecular forces to slip past one another between the layers.", "fibs": ["Viscosity"]}
{"text": "Summary
Intermolecular forces operate between the particles of matter.", "fibs": ["matter"]}
{"text": "Also, these do not include forces that hold atoms of a covalent molecule together through covalent bond.", "fibs": ["covalent"]}
{"text": "Competition between thermal energy and intermolecular interactions determines the state of matter.", "fibs": ["Competition"]}
{"text": "“Bulk” properties of matter such as behaviour of gases, characteristics of solids and liquids and change of state depend upon energy of constituent particles and the type of interaction between them.", "fibs": ["matter"]}
{"text": "Chemical properties of a substance do not change with change of state, but the reactivity depends upon the physical state.", "fibs": ["substance"]}
{"text": "Forces of interaction between gas molecules are negligible and are almost independent of their chemical nature.", "fibs": ["interaction"]}
{"text": "Interdependence of some observable properties namely pressure, volume, temperature and mass leads to different gas laws obtained from experimental studies on gases.", "fibs": ["Interdependence"]}
{"text": "Boyle’s law states that under isothermal condition, pressure of a fixed amount of a gas is inversely proportional to its volume.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "Charles’ law is a relationship between volume and absolute temperature under isobaric condition.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "It states that volume of a fixed amount of gas is directly proportional to its absolute temperature .", "fibs": ["volume"]}
{"text": "If state of a gas is represented by p1, V1 and T1 and it changes to state at p2, V2 and T2, then relationship between these two states is given by combined gas law according to which.", "fibs": ["state"]}
{"text": "Any one of the variables of this gas can be found out if other five variables are known.", "fibs": ["gas"]}
{"text": "Avogadro law states that equal volumes of all gases under same conditions of temperature and pressure contain equal number of molecules.", "fibs": ["law"]}
{"text": "Dalton’s law of partial pressure states that total pressure exerted by a mixture of non-reacting gases is equal to the sum of partial pressures exerted by them.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "Thus p = p1+p2+p3+ ... .", "fibs": ["p"]}
{"text": "Relationship between pressure, volume, temperature and number of moles of a gas describes its state and is called equation of state of the gas.", "fibs": ["pressure"]}
{"text": "Equation of state for ideal gas is pV=nRT, where R is a gas constant and its value depends upon units chosen for pressure, volume and temperature.", "fibs": ["Equation"]}
{"text": "At high pressure and low temperature intermolecular forces start operating strongly between the molecules of gases because they come close to each other.", "fibs": ["pressure"]}
{"text": "Under suitable temperature and pressure conditions gases can be liquified.", "fibs": ["temperature"]}
{"text": "Liquids may be considered as continuation of gas phase into a region of small volume and very strong molecular attractions.", "fibs": ["continuation"]}
{"text": "Some properties of liquids e.g., surface tension and viscosity are due to strong intermolecular attractive forces.", "fibs": ["surface"]}
